#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Human milk feeding is within the reference range while probiotic use is above it. The additional benefit of higher probiotic exposure in this context is uncertain and may vary by subgroup. Maintain policy-aligned use, robust governance, adherence checks, and safety surveillance using approved products.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_intestinal_microbiome_factors_human_milk_inbetween_probiotic_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Human milk feeding is within the reference range while probiotic use is below it. The additional benefit of routine probiotics in this context is uncertain and may vary by subgroup, so this finding alone does not support de-escalation or escalation. Review policy alignment, eligibility application, and practical barriers, including approved-product availability.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_intestinal_microbiome_factors_human_milk_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Human milk feeding is below the reference interquartile range. This may indicate reduced use of a protective feeding strategy associated with lower infection and NEC risk. Review lactation support, donor milk access, feeding pathways, and barriers to early and sustained human milk use.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_intestinal_microbiome_factors_human_milk_low_probiotic_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Human milk feeding is below the reference range while probiotic use is above the reference range. This may indicate greater reliance on probiotics in a setting with lower human milk exposure. Strengthen feeding support, as probiotics should complement rather than replace human milk-based protection, and ensure use remains restricted to approved products.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_intestinal_microbiome_factors_human_milk_low_probiotic_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Human milk feeding is below the reference range while probiotic use is within the reference range. This indicates reduced use of a key protective feeding strategy despite typical probiotic implementation. Focus on strengthening lactation and donor milk pathways while maintaining safe, policy-aligned probiotic practice.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_intestinal_microbiome_factors_human_milk_low_probiotic_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Human milk feeding and probiotic use are both below reference ranges. This pattern suggests reduced use of two microbiome-supportive strategies and may also reflect limited availability of approved probiotic products. Prioritise integrated improvement actions across lactation support, donor milk access, probiotic eligibility pathways, and procurement or regulatory constraints.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_intestinal_microbiome_factors_probiotic_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Probiotic use is above the reference interquartile range. This suggests broad implementation of a microbiome-support strategy where products are available and approved. Confirm governance quality, including approved products or strains, preparation and administration controls, and safety monitoring.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_intestinal_microbiome_factors_probiotic_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Probiotic use is below the reference interquartile range. This may indicate selective implementation, barriers in care pathways, or limited availability of safe, approved neonatal probiotic products. Review local eligibility criteria, procurement and regulatory constraints, prescribing pathways, and documentation quality.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_severe_infection_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Your severe infection rates (BSI, and HAP) exceed the reference population's 75th percentile. This requires comprehensive review of surveillance definitions, hand hygiene compliance, environmental cleaning, and other core infection prevention practices.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_severe_infection_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Your severe infection rates (BSI, and HAP) are below the reference population's 25th percentile. This favorable outcome suggests effective implementation of infection prevention strategies and warrants documentation of successful practices.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_vascular_catheter_rates_cvc_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Central venous catheter (CVC) utilization is above the reference interquartile range. This pattern may reflect higher clinical acuity, differing thresholds for central-line insertion, or local practices that favour earlier central access. It supports audit of CVC insertion indications, adherence to insertion and maintenance bundles, monitoring of central-line associated infection rates, and efforts to identify opportunities for earlier removal where clinically appropriate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_vascular_catheter_rates_cvc_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Central venous catheter (CVC) utilization is below the reference interquartile range. This may indicate comparatively lower central-access exposure, successful line-avoidance strategies, or differences in case mix and treatment intensity. While reduced central-line exposure can lower the risk of central-line associated complications, it is important to confirm that access adequacy for timely and effective treatment is maintained and that there are no barriers to appropriate central access when required. Review of escalation criteria, access pathways, and supply or staffing constraints can help interpret this finding.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_vascular_catheter_rates_pvc_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Peripheral venous catheter (PVC) utilization is above the reference interquartile range. This suggests greater peripheral-access exposure which may be favourable if it reduces central-line exposure and associated risks, but it can also increase peripheral-line workload and complication risk. Review indication criteria for PVCs, replacement frequency, dressing and site-care practices, and staff training for peripheral-line management. Consider whether higher PVC use is an intentional strategy to avoid central lines and evaluate associated outcomes, complication rates, and workload implications.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_vascular_catheter_rates_pvc_high_cvc_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Both PVC and CVC utilization are above reference ranges, indicating broadly elevated vascular-device exposure. This may reflect higher patient acuity, intensive treatment requirements, or local practices that favour vascular access. Elevated use of both peripheral and central devices increases the overall risk of device-associated complications and workload for clinical teams. This finding warrants comprehensive assessment of insertion indications, adherence to insertion and maintenance bundles for both PVCs and CVCs, opportunities to reduce avoidable device days, and monitoring of complication and infection rates to prioritise targeted prevention efforts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_vascular_catheter_rates_pvc_high_cvc_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Peripheral venous catheter (PVC) utilization is above the reference interquartile range while central venous catheter (CVC) utilization is within it. This pattern suggests greater reliance on peripheral access, which may be favourable if it reduces central-line exposure and associated risks, but it can also increase peripheral-line workload and complication risk. Review PVC indication criteria, replacement frequency, and peripheral-line management practices, ensure clear escalation pathways to central access when clinically required, and interpret findings alongside patient acuity and treatment needs.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_vascular_catheter_rates_pvc_high_cvc_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "PVC utilization is above the reference range while CVC utilization is below it. This pattern may suggest greater reliance on peripheral access and a deliberate strategy to avoid central-line exposure. This can be favourable if it reduces central-line associated risks, but it may increase peripheral-line workload and complication rates. Review PVC indication criteria, replacement intervals, and site-care practices, monitor peripheral complication rates, and ensure clear escalation pathways to central access when clinically required. Evaluate outcomes to confirm that reduced central-line use is delivering intended patient-safety benefits.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_vascular_catheter_rates_pvc_inbetween_cvc_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Central venous catheter (CVC) utilization is above the reference interquartile range while peripheral venous catheter (PVC) utilization is within it. Overall vascular catheter utilization may therefore be elevated compared with the reference population and should be interpreted in the context of patient acuity and case mix. This pattern may reflect higher clinical acuity, earlier escalation to central access, or differing thresholds for central-line use, and supports review of CVC insertion indications, adherence to insertion and maintenance bundles, and opportunities for early removal.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_vascular_catheter_rates_pvc_inbetween_cvc_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "PVC utilization is within the reference range while CVC utilization is below it. Overall vascular catheter utilisation may therefore be lower or similar to the reference population with particularly low central-line exposure. This could reflect successful central-line avoidance strategies, lower case acuity, or differences in access policies. While this can be favourable in terms of reducing central-line associated risks, confirm that access adequacy for necessary therapies is maintained and review escalation pathways and clinician training to ensure safe, timely treatment delivery.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_vascular_catheter_rates_pvc_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Peripheral venous catheter (PVC) utilization is below the reference interquartile range. This may indicate reduced peripheral-access exposure or more selective use of PVCs, reflecting either lower treatment intensity or a deliberate strategy to minimise peripheral cannulation. Interpret this in the context of overall vascular access patterns and treatment needs to ensure that reduced PVC use is not causing delays in therapy or increasing reliance on central access. Review local policies on PVC indication and replacement to confirm they align with best practice.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_vascular_catheter_rates_pvc_low_cvc_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "PVC utilization is below the reference range while CVC utilization is above it. This pattern may indicate earlier escalation to central access, lower use of peripheral bridging approaches, or a case mix demanding central access. Because higher CVC use increases the risk of central-line associated complications, this finding supports a focused review of vascular access decision pathways, criteria for escalation, and adherence to CVC insertion and maintenance bundles. Consider whether opportunities exist to safely increase peripheral strategies without compromising treatment needs.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_vascular_catheter_rates_pvc_low_cvc_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Peripheral venous catheter (PVC) utilization is below the reference interquartile range while central venous catheter (CVC) utilization is within it. Overall vascular catheter utilisation may therefore be slightly reduced compared with the reference population. This pattern could reflect selective use of PVCs, differences in peripheral-line policies, or a case mix requiring more central access relative to peripheral access. Interpret these findings alongside treatment intensity, escalation practices, and access adequacy to ensure that therapy delivery remains timely and appropriate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_vascular_catheter_rates_pvc_low_cvc_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Both PVC and CVC utilization are below reference ranges. This indicates a consistently lower overall vascular-device exposure which may reflect successful minimisation of invasive access, differences in case mix, or lower treatment intensity. While this can be favourable from an infection prevention perspective, it is important to ensure that adequate access for timely therapies is not compromised. Review clinical pathways, escalation criteria, and outcomes to confirm that low device exposure aligns with patient care needs and does not delay necessary interventions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Invasive ventilatory support utilization is above the reference interquartile range. This may reflect higher respiratory acuity, lower intubation thresholds, or prolonged invasive ventilation. Review intubation indications, weaning practices, infection-prevention measures, and invasive-ventilation outcomes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Invasive ventilatory support utilization is below the reference interquartile range. This may reflect successful non-invasive support, lower case acuity, or different intubation thresholds. Confirm that reduced invasive use is clinically appropriate and does not delay needed intubation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_niv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Non-invasive ventilatory support utilization is above the reference interquartile range. This may reflect an intentional strategy to reduce invasive exposure and can be favourable from an infection-prevention perspective. Review non-invasive initiation criteria, monitoring, failure and escalation rates, and staff training to confirm safety and effectiveness.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_niv_high_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Non-invasive and invasive support are both above reference ranges, indicating elevated use across modalities. This may reflect high respiratory burden or variable escalation practices. Review disease severity, modality transition decisions, and opportunities to optimise support duration.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_niv_high_inv_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Non-invasive support is above the reference range while invasive support is within the reference range. This profile is compatible with increased non-invasive support and potentially lower invasive exposure. Assess non-invasive success and failure rates, and identify subgroups driving higher exposure.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_niv_high_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Non-invasive support is above the reference range while invasive support is below the reference range. This may indicate a deliberate non-invasive strategy and can be favourable for infection prevention if safely delivered. Review workload, device management, and escalation safety.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_niv_inbetween_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Non-invasive support is within the reference range while invasive support is above it. This discordant profile suggests invasive exposure concentrated in a subgroup. Investigate case mix, escalation patterns, and outcomes for that subgroup.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_niv_inbetween_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Non-invasive support is within the reference range while invasive support is below the reference range. This may indicate effective non-invasive support and reduced invasive exposure. Review non-invasive success rates, escalation timing, and clinical outcomes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_niv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Non-invasive ventilatory support utilization is below the reference interquartile range. This may indicate limited non-invasive use, earlier progression to invasive modes, or lower respiratory burden. Interpret this with invasive-support patterns and case mix, and review whether safe expansion of non-invasive support is feasible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_niv_low_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Non-invasive support is below the reference range while invasive support is above the reference range. This profile suggests earlier or more frequent progression to intubation. Review escalation thresholds, intubation criteria, and drivers of prolonged invasive duration.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_niv_low_inv_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Non-invasive support is below the reference range while invasive support is within the reference range. This may reflect limited non-invasive use with proportionate invasive exposure. Review modality selection, escalation practice, and opportunities to strengthen safe non-invasive support.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_niv_low_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Non-invasive and invasive support are both below reference ranges. This suggests broadly reduced respiratory-support exposure, potentially due to case mix or lower acuity. Confirm that modality access and escalation remain adequate when respiratory status worsens.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support utilization is above the reference interquartile range. This pattern may reflect higher respiratory acuity, lower thresholds for support initiation, or prolonged support durations. Review case mix, initiation and weaning criteria, and opportunities to reduce avoidable support duration while maintaining safe escalation pathways.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support and invasive support are both above reference ranges. This indicates elevated respiratory burden with increased invasive exposure. Conduct a comprehensive review of airway management, duration of invasive ventilation, weaning, and infection-prevention measures.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_inv_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is above the reference range while invasive support is within the reference range. This may reflect increased use of non-invasive support, which can be favourable from an infection-prevention perspective. Review non-invasive protocols, failure rates, and escalation thresholds, and assess whether higher total support burden is driven by prolonged duration.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is above the reference range while invasive support is below the reference range. This pattern is compatible with greater reliance on non-invasive modalities and can be favourable from an infection-prevention perspective. Review non-invasive protocols, failure rates, and escalation thresholds to ensure timely intubation when required.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_niv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support and non-invasive support are both above reference ranges. This may reflect substantial respiratory burden alongside high use of non-invasive pathways, which can be IPC-favourable if safe. Review capacity, staff training, failure rates, and outcomes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_niv_high_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall, non-invasive, and invasive ventilatory support rates are all above reference ranges. This indicates substantially elevated respiratory-support burden across modalities. Conduct comprehensive review of respiratory pathways, escalation decisions, support duration, and infection-prevention practices.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_niv_high_inv_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support and non-invasive support are above the reference range while invasive support is within the reference range. This may indicate high non-invasive exposure without excess invasive escalation. Assess non-invasive success, subgroup contributions, and escalation safety.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_niv_high_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is above the reference range, with non-invasive support above and invasive support below the reference range. This profile is compatible with emphasis on non-invasive pathways and may be IPC-favourable if safe. Review failure, escalation, and outcome metrics.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_niv_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is above the reference range while non-invasive support is within the reference range. This suggests increased total burden not fully explained by non-invasive exposure alone. Evaluate case mix, support-duration distribution, and weaning practices.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_niv_inbetween_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support and invasive support are above the reference range while non-invasive support is within the reference range. This indicates increased invasive burden contributing to higher total exposure. Review intubation practices, invasive duration, and patient outcomes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_niv_inbetween_inv_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is above the reference range while component modalities are both within the reference range. This suggests increased total burden not attributable to one modality alone. Audit support duration, case mix, and data classification to identify underlying drivers.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_niv_inbetween_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is above the reference range while non-invasive support is within the reference range and invasive support is below the reference range. This may reflect prolonged non-invasive durations driving total burden without parallel invasive increase. Review duration patterns and escalation timing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_niv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is above the reference range while non-invasive support is below the reference range. This discordant profile may indicate greater reliance on invasive ventilation or prolonged invasive duration. Review initiation and escalation thresholds, intubation practices, and drivers of invasive days.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_niv_low_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is above the reference range, with invasive support above the reference range and non-invasive support below the reference range. This pattern indicates substantial invasive-driven burden. Investigate case mix, intubation thresholds, duration, and outcomes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_niv_low_inv_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is above the reference range while non-invasive support is low and invasive support is within the reference range. This may indicate reduced non-invasive use despite high overall burden. Review escalation choices, modality selection, and weaning practice.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_high_niv_low_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is above the reference range while both non-invasive and invasive components are below the reference range. This discordant profile may indicate data-classification or denominator issues. Review metric definitions, data completeness, and support coding workflows.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_inbetween_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is within the reference range while invasive support is above the reference range. This indicates invasive ventilation concentrated in a subgroup. Review intubation criteria, duration, and outcomes, and assess whether earlier non-invasive optimisation is possible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_inbetween_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is within the reference range while invasive support is below the reference range. This may reflect effective non-invasive support and can be favourable from an IPC perspective. Review escalation-to-intubation metrics, thresholds, and outcomes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_inbetween_niv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is within the reference range while non-invasive support is above the reference range. This suggests a preference for non-invasive modalities within a typical overall burden and may be favourable from an IPC perspective. Evaluate escalation rates and clinical outcomes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_inbetween_niv_high_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is within the reference range while both non-invasive and invasive components are above the reference range. This discordant profile suggests heterogeneity across subgroups or modality-classification differences. Perform subgroup analysis and verify metric definitions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_inbetween_niv_high_inv_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is within the reference range while non-invasive support is above the reference range and invasive support is within the reference range. This may indicate greater use of non-invasive pathways without excess invasive exposure. Assess whether specific subgroups drive this pattern and confirm escalation safety.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_inbetween_niv_high_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is within the reference range while non-invasive support is above the reference range and invasive support is below the reference range. This pattern may represent successful non-invasive support with lower invasive exposure and potential IPC benefit. Review safety outcomes and escalation reliability.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_inbetween_niv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is within the reference range while non-invasive support is below the reference range. This may reflect earlier progression to invasive modes or under-use of non-invasive support. Review initiation thresholds, decision-making, and modality availability.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_inbetween_niv_low_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is within the reference range while invasive support is above the reference range and non-invasive support is low. This suggests invasive exposure concentrated in a subgroup. Review intubation criteria, duration, outcomes, and denominator consistency.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_inbetween_niv_low_inv_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is within the reference range while non-invasive support is low and invasive support is within the reference range. This may reflect limited non-invasive use with proportionate invasive exposure. Review initiation thresholds, modality access, and outcomes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_inbetween_niv_low_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is within the reference range while non-invasive and invasive components are both below the reference range. This may indicate few infants need modality-specific support or differences in modality assignment. Verify data capture and assess whether local pathways explain low component rates.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support utilization is below the reference interquartile range. This may reflect lower respiratory acuity, effective prevention and weaning practices, or local thresholds for initiating support. While lower support exposure can be favourable, confirm that access to escalation remains timely and that reduced use is not associated with adverse outcomes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_low_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is below the reference range while invasive support is above the reference range. This discordant profile suggests concentrated invasive burden in a subgroup and warrants focused review of intubation criteria, invasive duration drivers, and outcomes. Verify subgroup case mix and denominator assignment to support valid interpretation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_low_inv_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is below the reference range while invasive support is within the reference range. This may indicate invasive ventilation concentrated in a smaller subgroup. Verify denominators and case mix, and review escalation pathways and outcomes for that subgroup.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_low_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support and invasive support are both below reference ranges. This suggests lower total respiratory exposure, including reduced invasive exposure. Confirm that low invasive use remains appropriate and is not associated with delayed intubation when needed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_low_niv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is below the reference range while non-invasive support is above the reference range. This pattern may reflect preference for non-invasive pathways, which can be favourable for infection prevention if safe. Review failure and escalation rates, workload, and outcomes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_low_niv_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is below the reference range while non-invasive support is within the reference range. This may indicate selective non-invasive use in a low-burden population. Review initiation criteria, denominators, and targeting of non-invasive support.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_low_niv_inbetween_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is below the reference range while invasive support is above the reference range. This may indicate invasive-driven burden concentrated in a small subgroup. Review case mix, denominator assignment, and drivers of prolonged invasive support.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_low_niv_inbetween_inv_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is below the reference range while component modalities are within the reference range. This suggests lower total support burden with broadly typical modality distribution. Continue trend monitoring and review any shifts in escalation patterns.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_low_niv_inbetween_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support is below the reference range, with non-invasive support within the reference range and invasive support below the reference range. This may reflect targeted non-invasive support in a low-burden population. Assess safety outcomes and timeliness of escalation when needed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_low_niv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall ventilatory support and non-invasive support are both below reference ranges. This suggests a generally lower respiratory-support burden, potentially related to case mix or effective prevention and weaning. Confirm that escalation pathways remain timely for infants who deteriorate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_low_niv_low_inv_high
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall and non-invasive support are below the reference range, while invasive support is above the reference range. This discordant pattern suggests high invasive exposure in a subgroup and warrants review of intubation practices, invasive-duration drivers, and outcomes. Confirm subgroup case mix and denominator consistency when interpreting this pattern.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_low_niv_low_inv_inbetween
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall and non-invasive support are below the reference range, while invasive support is within the reference range. This may indicate invasive ventilation concentrated in a smaller high-acuity subgroup. Verify denominators, case mix, and escalation policies for that subgroup.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: outlier grouped_ventilatory_support_rates_vs_low_niv_low_inv_low
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_sR.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overall, non-invasive, and invasive ventilatory support rates are all below reference ranges. This consistent low-exposure profile may reflect lower respiratory acuity or effective prevention and weaning. Confirm escalation readiness and modality access for infants who require support.\n"
msgstr ""

