#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_introduction.Rmd:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "This is a [NeoIPC Surveillance](https://neoipc.org/surveillance/ \"Link to the surveillance section of the NeoIPC website\") analysis that you can use to assess infection rates in your neonatal unit. If you have your own data collected using the same or a comparable method, you can compare them with the reference values presented in this document and identify any anomalies and potential for improvement.\n"
msgstr "See on [NeoIPC Surveillance](https://neoipc.org/surveillance/ \"Link NeoIPC veebisaidi järelevalve osale\") analüüs, mida saate kasutada oma vastsündinute osakonna nakkusjuhtude määra hindamiseks. Kui teil on oma andmed, mis on kogutud sama või sarnase meetodiga, saate neid võrrelda käesolevas dokumendis esitatud võrdlusväärtustega ning tuvastada kõrvalekalded ja parandamisvõimalused. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_introduction.Rmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "The following summary presents key surveillance metrics for this report:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_patient-population.Rmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "The NeoIPC surveillance system focuses on high-risk neonates to ensure sustainable continuous monitoring. Patients with a birth weight below 1500 g and/or gestational age below 32 weeks at birth are included if admitted within the first 120 days of life. The following figures show the composition of your patient population based on the filter settings specified in the report header.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_nosocomial_infections.Rmd:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "Healthcare-associated infections represent the primary endpoint of NeoIPC surveillance. In your unit, `r dR$own$numberOfSevereInfections` severe infections were recorded in `r dR$own$numberOfPatients` patients, resulting in an average of `r dR$own$averageSevereInfectionsPerPatient` infections per patient`r if (!is.null(dR$ref)) paste0(\", compared to \", dR$ref$numberOfSevereInfections, \" infections in \", dR$ref$numberOfPatients, \" reference patients (average: \", dR$ref$averageSevereInfectionsPerPatient, \")\")`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_nosocomial_infections.Rmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "The following tables present incidence density rates for sepsis/bloodstream infections, pneumonia, and necrotizing enterocolitis, as well as device-associated infection rates.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_infectious-agents.Rmd:2
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "Epidemiology of the infectious agents causing nosocomial infections in neonatology is complex and there is a lot of potential for bias. While low diagnostic sensitivity (low blood volume) and specificity (contamination) are a general problem in the neonatal population, the lack of availability of some or all means of microbiological diagnostics, or the lack of financial resources can have a strong effect on the detection rates in resource-constrained settings.\n"
msgid "Understanding the epidemiology of infectious agents causing nosocomial infections is crucial but complex. Diagnostic challenges including low sensitivity (limited blood volume) and specificity (contamination risk) are inherent to the neonatal population. Additionally, availability of microbiological diagnostics and resources can significantly affect detection rates.\n"
msgstr "Neonatoloogias haiglanakkusi põhjustavate nakkusetekitajate epidemioloogia on keeruline ja sisaldab palju potentsiaalset eelarvamust. Kuigi madal diagnostiline tundlikkus (madal vere maht) ja spetsiifilisus (saastumine) on üldine probleem vastsündinute populatsioonis, võib mõnede või kõigi mikrobioloogiliste diagnostikavahendite kättesaamatus või rahaliste vahendite puudus mõjutada tugevalt avastamismäära ressursipiirangutega keskkondades.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_infectious-agents.Rmd:3
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "In total, `r dR$numberOfInfectiousAgents` infectious agents were detected in the `r dR$numberOfInfectionsWithAgent` infections that were reported to have yielded at least one agent from either the primary infection and/or the secondary bloodstream infection resulting from it (@tbl-agent-per-infection-rate). These `r dR$numberOfInfectionsWithAgent` diagnostic-positive infections out of `r dR$overallNumberOfInfections` overall infections represent an Infectious Agent Detection Rate of `r dR$infectiousAgentDetectionRate` per 100 infections (@tbl-infectious-agent-detection-rate).\n"
msgid "In your data, `r dR$own$numberOfInfectiousAgents` infectious agents were detected in `r dR$own$numberOfInfectionsWithAgent` infections out of `r dR$own$overallNumberOfInfections` total infections, representing an infectious agent detection rate of `r dR$own$infectiousAgentDetectionRate` per 100 infections. The following tables provide detailed information on pathogen distribution and antimicrobial resistance patterns.\n"
msgstr "Kokku tuvastati `r dR$numberOfInfectiousAgents` nakkusetekitajat `r dR$numberOfInfectionsWithAgent` nakkusjuhtumi puhul, mille puhul teatati vähemalt ühe nakkusetekitaja esinemisest esmase nakkuse ja/või sellest tuleneva teisese vereringe nakkuse korral (@tbl-agent-per-infection-rate). Need `r dR$numberOfInfectionsWithAgent` diagnoosipositiivset nakkusjuhtu `r dR$overallNumberOfInfections` nakkusjuhtumi koguarvust tähendavad nakkusetekitajate avastamismäära `r dR$infectiousAgentDetectionRate` 100 nakkusjuhtumi kohta (@tbl-infectious-agent-detection-rate).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_risk-factors.Rmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Exposure to invasive devices and protective interventions significantly influence infection risk in neonatal intensive care. The following table presents the density rates for central venous catheters, peripheral venous catheters, invasive ventilation, as well as protective factors including human milk feeding, kangaroo mother care, and probiotic administration.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_surgery.Rmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Surgical interventions in neonates carry inherent infection risks. The following tables present rates for various surgical procedures and associated surgical site infections, as well as secondary bloodstream infections following other types of healthcare-associated infections.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_fig-intro-birth-weight.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Birth weight distribution is a key indicator of your unit's patient population characteristics. Understanding the weight distribution of admitted neonates helps contextualize infection rates and other outcomes, as lower birth weight is associated with increased vulnerability to healthcare-associated infections. @fig-bw shows both the frequency distribution (histogram with density curve) and summary statistics (boxplot with quartiles) of birth weights in your unit, enabling comparison with your patient case mix relative to reference data when available.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_fig-intro-gestational-age.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Gestational age distribution provides essential context for interpreting clinical outcomes in your neonatal unit. Extremely premature infants face substantially higher risks of complications and infections compared to more mature neonates. @fig-ga illustrates both the frequency distribution (histogram with density curve) and summary statistics (boxplot with quartiles) of gestational ages at birth, allowing you to assess how your patient population's maturity profile compares to reference data when available.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-incidence-density.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "@tbl-incidence-density-rates presents the incidence density rates for the most important healthcare-associated infections (HAI) in your neonatal unit. Incidence density rates are calculated per 1,000 patient days, allowing for meaningful comparison between units with different patient volumes and lengths of stay. Regular monitoring of these rates enables you to identify trends, evaluate the effectiveness of infection prevention measures, and compare your performance against reference data from other participating units.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-device-associated.qmd:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "Device-associated infections represent a significant burden in neonatal intensive care. @tbl-device-associated-incidence-density-rates shows infection rates specifically linked to the use of invasive devices such as central venous catheters and mechanical ventilation. By tracking device-associated infection rates separately, you can assess the safety of device utilization in your unit and identify specific areas where targeted interventions may reduce infection risk. Lower rates may indicate successful implementation of device care bundles and infection prevention protocols.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced div block ({.callout-note})
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-device-associated.qmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Device-associated infections are defined temporally according to the\n"
"[NeoIPC Core Protocol](https://neoipc.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/NeoIPC-Surveillance_Core-Module-Protocol.pdf).\n"
"Infections occurring during device use represent potential rather than proven causal relationships.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-agent-per-infection.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Understanding which pathogens cause infections in your unit is essential for targeted prevention strategies and empirical treatment decisions. @tbl-agent-per-infection-rate presents the detection rates of infectious agents per infection type, highlighting the microbial epidemiology of healthcare-associated infections in your neonatal population. Patterns in pathogen distribution can inform antimicrobial stewardship efforts and help identify potential sources of transmission requiring specific control measures.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-abr-infection.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Antimicrobial resistance poses a critical threat to vulnerable neonatal patients. @tbl-abr-infection-rate displays infection rates caused by resistant pathogens such as MRSA, VRE, and third-generation cephalosporin-resistant organisms. Monitoring these rates is crucial for assessing the burden of drug-resistant infections in your unit and evaluating the effectiveness of antimicrobial stewardship programs. Elevated rates may signal the need for enhanced infection control measures, antibiotic prescribing review, or environmental screening protocols.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-infectious-agent-detection.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "The pattern of pathogen detection across different infection types provides valuable insights into your unit's microbial ecology. @tbl-infectious-agent-detection-rate shows how frequently specific infectious agents are identified in various types of healthcare-associated infections. Understanding these detection patterns helps in developing targeted surveillance strategies, appropriate empirical therapy guidelines, and infection prevention protocols tailored to your unit's specific pathogen profile.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-resistance-test.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Antimicrobial susceptibility testing (AST) is fundamental to both individual patient management and population-level surveillance. @tbl-resistance-test-rate presents the rate at which pathogens isolated from infections undergo testing for certain relevant antimicrobial resistances. High testing rates ensure reliable data for antimicrobial stewardship programs and enable accurate assessment of resistance trends. Lower rates may indicate gaps in microbiological diagnostic capacity or protocols that could limit your ability to detect and respond to emerging resistance patterns.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-risk-density.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Risk factors and protective factors significantly influence infection outcomes in neonatal care. @tbl-risk-density-rates shows the utilization density of key interventions including invasive devices (which increase infection risk) and protective measures such as human milk feeding, kangaroo care, and probiotics. Benchmarking these utilization rates helps identify opportunities to reduce unnecessary device use while optimizing evidence-based protective interventions. The balance between risk and protective factors reflects your unit's overall approach to infection prevention.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-surgical-procedure.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Surgical procedures represent a major risk factor for healthcare-associated infections in neonatal intensive care. @tbl-surgical-procedure-rates presents rates of various surgical procedures performed in your unit, normalized per 1,000 patient days. Understanding your surgical case mix is essential for interpreting infection rates and implementing appropriate surgical site infection prevention protocols. Comparison with reference data helps contextualize your unit's surgical workload and associated infection risks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-secondary-bsi.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Secondary bloodstream infections occur when primary infections at other sites seed the bloodstream, representing serious complications that significantly impact patient outcomes. @tbl-secondary-bsi-rates shows the rate at which different primary infection types progress to secondary bloodstream involvement. High rates of secondary BSI may indicate delayed diagnosis, inadequate source control, or particularly virulent pathogens, and warrant careful review of clinical protocols and infection management strategies.\n"
msgstr ""

